    id: 'new-15',
    slug: 'price-elasticity',
    name: 'Price Elasticity of Demand',
    category: 'Marketing',
    subcategory: 'Pricing Strategy',
    definition: 'Price Elasticity of Demand PED measures how responsive the quantity demanded of a good or service is to changes in its price. It is calculated as the percentage change in quantity demanded divided by the percentage change in price. If PED is greater than 1 in absolute value, demand is elastic meaning customers are price-sensitive and a small price change causes a large change in quantity demanded. If PED is less than 1, demand is inelastic meaning customers are less price-sensitive and change little with price changes. If PED equals 1, it is unitary elastic meaning revenue stays constant as price changes.',
    simpleExplanation: 'Price elasticity tells you whether you can raise prices without losing customers. Gasoline has inelastic demand people need to drive regardless of price. Luxury handbags have elastic demand people will wait for a sale or buy a different brand if prices go up too much.',
    example: 'A coffee shop raises the price of a latte from $4 to $5 (25% increase). Sales drop from 100 to 80 per day (20% decrease). PED = |-20%/25%| = 0.8. Since 0.8 < 1, demand is inelastic. Revenue actually increased from $400 to $400 revenue stayed same. The coffee shop could potentially raise prices further without losing significant customers.',
    whyItMatters: 'Understanding price elasticity is crucial for pricing decisions. If demand is inelastic, raising prices increases revenue. If demand is elastic, raising prices decreases revenue. Elasticity also affects tax policy governments tax inelastic goods like cigarettes and alcohol more heavily because consumption changes less. For businesses, elasticity varies by segment, product, and time, enabling sophisticated pricing strategies.',
    formula: 'PED = % Change in Quantity Demanded / % Change in Price | %ΔQ / %ΔP |',
    formulaDescription: 'Price Elasticity equals the absolute value of the percentage change in quantity demanded divided by the percentage change in price. If PED > 1, demand is elastic price-sensitive. If PED < 1, demand is inelastic not price-sensitive.',
    relatedTerms: ['pricing-strategy', 'supply-and-demand', 'revenue-management', 'value-based-pricing', 'surge-pricing', 'dynamic-pricing'],
    interviewQuestions: ['How would you determine the price elasticity for a new product?', 'What factors make demand more elastic or inelastic?', 'How does price elasticity affect revenue optimization?', 'How would you use elasticity to design a pricing strategy for a SaaS product?', 'What is the relationship between price elasticity and substitute goods?'],
    commonMistakes: ['Assuming elasticity is constant it changes over time, by segment, and with availability of substitutes.', 'Forgetting that elasticity applies in both directions price increases and decreases, with different magnitudes.', 'Not considering competitor reactions your price change may trigger competitor price changes, altering your expected elasticity.'],
    sharkTankExample: 'When a food entrepreneur pitches their premium condiment, Kevin asks about price elasticity. If they raise prices by 10%, how many customers do they lose? The founder who knows their PED data impresses the sharks by demonstrating they have tested different price points and found demand is inelastic up to a certain threshold.',
    realCompanyExample: 'Uber uses dynamic pricing based on real-time elasticity. During surge pricing, prices increase to reduce excess demand and attract more drivers. Uber knows that in bad weather or after concerts, demand becomes temporarily inelastic, allowing surge pricing to clear the market efficiently.',
    visualDiagram: 'Price Increase of 10% -> Elastic Demand: Quantity drops 20% -> Revenue Decreases || Inelastic Demand: Quantity drops 3% -> Revenue Increases || Unit Elastic: Quantity drops 10% -> Revenue Unchanged',
    quickSummary: 'Price Elasticity of Demand measures customer sensitivity to price changes. Elastic demand (PED > 1) means customers are price-sensitive; raising prices reduces revenue. Inelastic demand (PED < 1) means customers are less sensitive; raising prices increases revenue.',
    faqs: [
      { question: 'What makes demand more inelastic?', answer: 'Necessities, few substitutes, small percentage of income, brand loyalty, and short time horizons make demand more inelastic.' },
      { question: 'How is elasticity used in pricing strategy?', answer: 'Companies estimate elasticity to set optimal prices. Software enables real-time testing of different price points to measure elasticity empirically.' },
      { question: 'What is cross-price elasticity?', answer: 'Cross-price elasticity measures how demand for one good changes when the price of another good changes. It is positive for substitutes and negative for complements.' },
    ],
    references: ['Mankiw, N.G. (2020). Principles of Economics.', 'Dolan, R. & Simon, H. (1996). Power Pricing.', 'Nagel, T. & Holden, R. (2002). The Strategy and Tactics of Pricing.'],
    tags: ['price elasticity', 'pricing', 'demand', 'economics', 'revenue', 'microeconomics', 'marketing'],
